Convolutional Neural Networks for Tree Bark Classification¶

For this week's exercise you will build a model for tree bark classification. The data set we will use is this one here: https://www.vicos.si/Downloads/TRUNK12 (just above 1GB)

One way to solve this task is to use the features computed by different layers of a standard convolutional neural network, feel free to pick one here: https://keras.io/api/applications/ That page also contains the code examples for extracting features from different network layers and finetuning models.

You don't need to fine tune models though - given the small data set size it's a perfectly reasonable approach to just extract activations for all images and use a simple model like KNN or logistic regression (which would essentially amount to fine tuning).

If you have time and/or a GPU, you could try various layers of VGG (https://keras.io/api/applications/vgg/#vgg16-function). If you don't you could experiment with smaller/faster CNNs as NASNET (https://keras.io/api/applications/nasnet/#nasnetmobile-function) or MobileNet (https://keras.io/api/applications/mobilenet/#mobilenetv2-function).

The goal of this task is that you explore how the most important feature of tree/bark recognition can be predicted with the features in earlier or later layers of a CNN.

There will be no guidance with a pre-implemented notebook for data preprocessing, but we're happy to answer questions.

Please submit your final notebook (without the data set). The notebook should show how your model is performing on a test split of 20% for at least an early layer and one of the last layers of a CNN.

Splitting the data¶

Split images into train and validation data (60%, 40%):

In [9]:
def split_data(subset, data_dir=data_dir, validation_split=0.4, batch_size=batch_size, img_height=img_height, img_width=img_width):
    ds = preprocessing.image_dataset_from_directory(
      data_dir,
      validation_split=validation_split,
      subset=subset,
      labels='inferred',
      label_mode='int',
      color_mode='rgb',
      seed=13353,
      image_size=(img_height, img_width),
      batch_size=batch_size)
    return ds

train_ds = split_data("training")
val_ds = split_data("validation")

Building the model¶

Use MobileNet V2 model as pre-trained model¶

Without the classifier part, so include_top is set to false. We will also use some of the later layers of the model.

In [39]:
base_model = MobileNetV2(input_shape=input_shape, weights='imagenet', include_top=False)
In [41]:
base_model = models.Model(inputs=base_model.input, outputs=base_model.layers[-12].output)

Rescale pixel values¶

Each Keras Application expects a specific kind of input preprocessing. For MobileNet, we call tf.keras.applications.mobilenet.preprocess_input on our inputs before passing them to the model. mobilenet.preprocess_input will scale input pixels between -1 and 1.

In [42]:
preprocess_input = applications.mobilenet_v2.preprocess_input

Adding new classifier layers¶

We're using the pre-trained model as a feature extraction component. We then want to train the new layers of the model without updating the weights of the MobileNetV2 layers (setting the trainable attribute to false). This allows the new output layers to learn to interpret the learned features of the base model.

In [43]:
# Feature extraction example

images, labels = next(iter(train_ds))
features = base_model.predict(images)

print(features.shape)

In [44]:
# Freeze the convolutional base
base_model.trainable = False

# Average pooling layer: Converts the 224x224x3 image into a 7x7x160 block of features
average_pooling_layer = layers.GlobalAveragePooling2D()

# Fully-connected layer
fc_layer = layers.Dense(128, activation='relu')

# Output layer
prediction_layer = layers.Dense(num_classes, activation='softmax')
In [45]:
# Put everything together
inputs = Input(shape=input_shape)
x = preprocess_input(inputs)
x = base_model(x, training = False)
x = average_pooling_layer(x)
x = fc_layer(x)
x = layers.Dropout(0.2)(x)
outputs = prediction_layer(x)
model = tf.keras.Model(inputs, outputs)

Compile the model¶

We're using the Adam optimizer with a learning rate of 0.001 (see default parameters above). The Sparse Categorical Cross Entropy loss is used.

In [47]:
model.compile(optimizer=optimizers.Adam(learning_rate=learning_rate),
        loss=SparseCategoricalCrossentropy(from_logits=True),
        metrics=['sparse_categorical_accuracy'])

scores = tf.nn.softmax(predictions)
pred = np.empty((32,), dtype='int32')
for index, score in enumerate(scores):
    pred[index] = np.argmax(score)

Using earlier layers of the CNN¶

Now what if we were to use the earlier layers of the base model instead of a later one? We will use the output of the 'block_16_project_BN' layer of MobileNet V2 which is the 17th layer of the model.
